{"id":"1501.01889","submitter":"John LaChapelle","authors":"J. LaChapelle","title":"Functional Integration on Topological Groups II: Functional Mellin\n  Transforms","comments":"This is the second of two papers representing an expanded version of\n  arXiv:1308.1063","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Conventional functional/path integrals used in physics most often are defined\nas infinite-dimensional analogs of Fourier transforms. The infinite-dimensional\nanalogs of Mellin transforms similarly define a class of functional integrals.\nThe associated functional integrals are useful tools for probing\nnon-commutative function spaces in general and $C^\\ast$-algebras in particular.\nFunctional Mellin transforms can be used to define functional resolvents,\nfunctional complex powers, functional traces, functional logarithms, and\nfunctional determinants. Several aspects of these objects are explored and\napplied to various constructs in mathematical physics. Two are of particular\nnote: 1) Certain fractional power operators (perhaps coincidentally) reproduce\nthe channels and crossing symmetry of tree-level open tachyon string scattering\nprocesses, and their algebraic product parallels the gauge-gravity relation of\nKawai-Lewellen-Tye. 2) The functional complex power of the generating\nfunctional of $n$-point functions in QFT and its functional logarithm are\nemployed to justify the replica trick.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 8 Jan 2015 16:00:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 13 Dec 2019 23:26:50 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 29 Mar 2022 19:53:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-03-31"}
